# Code Style Guidelines

## General Principles

- Prefer consistency with the existing codebase over personal preference.
- Favor readability, maintainability, and simplicity.
- Avoid unnecessary complexity, abstraction, or premature optimization.
- Write code that is easy to understand and modify by other developers.
- Add comments only where they are needed: non-obvious behavior, important invariants, workarounds, or security/performance rationale.
- Do not add comments that merely repeat what the code already says, or boilerplate on every function unless the project already requires it for public APIs.

---

## TypeScript and JavaScript

### Semicolons

- Omit statement-terminating semicolons when the project consistently follows ASI (Automatic Semicolon Insertion) style.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid
const x = 1;

// ✅ Prefer
const x = 1